      <Subject xmlns="urn:xmlns:nl:pop-project:vocab:Subjects#">D51000</Subject>
      <Abstract xml:lang="en">The aim of the proposed project is to elucidate how cognitioninfluences action control. In tasks that depend on the cognitive control of action, we will manipulatetask related attention, expectation, learning and the level of fatigue. We will investigate the influenceof these cognitive factors on the activity in different brain areas and the spinal cord, and on thestrength of their cooperative interactions. Our central working hypothesis is that cognitivefactors play a key role in action control through modulating neuronal dynamics, in particular oscillatoryneuronal synchronization. Furthermore, we hypothesize that increased cortical synchronizationaffects neuronal firing at the spinal level. We will integrate our experimental observations into abiologically plausible model that encompasses the involved cortical and spinal circuitry as well aseffects of the cognitive manipulations. The model will incorporate experimental findings,guide the refinement of experimental procedures and try to predict experimental outcomes. b. Cortical neuronal activity will be assessed with high temporalresolution using whole head high density EEG and MEG. In addition, simultaneously recorded highdensity surface EMG of task relevant muscles will provide a measure of the activity of individualspinal motoneurons. Transcranial magnetic stimulation (TMS) will be used to probe the level ofcortical excitability. Subjects will perform simple and complex motor tasks. These tasks will be designedto systematically vary task related cognitive variables. Also, using dual task paradigms thatcombine a semi-automatic motor task with a demanding cognitive task, we will probe their mutualinterference. We will address the cognitive influences on oscillatory synchronization between (i)visual and motor cortical areas, (ii) left and right motor cortex and (iii) motor cortex and spinal motoneurons.The model structure and its parameters will be adapted to input provided by the experimentalresults. The know-how with respect to neural network principles, cortico-spinal connections andnon-linear dynamical systems behavior will be integrated. c. The conceptual innovation of the proposed project is to usecognitive tasks as well as dual task interference to test directly the functional role of cortico-corticaland cortical-spinal coherence. The methodological and technical innovation consists of a unique</Abstract>
